value.name: SBUHacks
value.description:
We expect to host between 200-400 students (“hackers”) on our campus, depending on the amount of funding we receive and the marketing success we will have. Hackers apply over a month-long period, and we will accept as many as we can support. Hackers pay no cost to participate (outside of personal transportation). 

We run three “main tracks”, which are overall themes (e.g. for this year these are student experience, interdisciplinary, and equitable technology). Hackers choose at most two main tracks to guide their development over the course of the hackathon. We do not impose any constraints on what students invent, aside from the implicit value of a project that aligns more closely with the chosen track’s theme. 

The event will run from Friday, November 7, beginning at 6:30pm with check in, until Sunday, November 9, ending at around 3pm (+/- 30min) The event will take place on Stony Brook University campus. 

There will be a main “hacking period” from 9pm on Friday until 7am on Sunday. During this period, students will be working on their projects, but other wellness, social, and technical workshops/events will be taking place concurrently. We currently have 6 workshop slots planned in which other student organizations may sign up to give workshops, however these are not exclusive to student organizations. We additionally have a designated Company/Sponsor Panel slot scheduled. These slots range from Friday night, through Saturday evening (barring overnight Friday-Saturday).

Judging will take place from 11am-1pm on Sunday, during which students will pitch their inventions, followed by an awards ceremony and closing.

First-Gen Week Scavenger Hunt Challenge

SCAVENGER HUNT INSTRUCTIONS
Submission Deadline: MONDAY, NOVEMBER 10, 2025 by 5 PM 

Celebrate National First-Generation College Celebration Day with an exciting Scavenger Hunt across all Stony Brook University campus locations! This interactive experience invites students to explore campus landmarks, learn about university traditions, and discover valuable resources—all while competing to win raffle prizes.

Whether it’s snapping a selfie with Wolfie, finding campus murals, meeting First-Gen faculty and staff, or capturing clips for Seawolf Questions—this hunt is packed with fun challenges designed to connect you more deeply to your campus community.

  1. Explore the scavenger hunt prompts for Stony Brook, Southampton, or Manhattan (or all three!)

  2. Document your completed activities with photos or short video clips (your face does not need to be visible)

  3. Select and upload up to 5 submissions to a Google Drive folder

  4. Share the folder with: first_generation@stonybrook.edu

  5. Each submitted photo or video (max 5) = one raffle entry!

Submission Deadline: Monday, November 10, 2025
Note: Challenges can be completed in any order. Please follow all campus guidelines—safety first, fun always!

‚úÖ Explore campus resource hubs like the Food Pantry, Tutoring Center, Sensory Spaces, and more

value.name: SBUHacks
value.description:
We expect to host between 200-400 students (“hackers”) on our campus, depending on the amount of funding we receive and the marketing success we will have. Hackers apply over a month-long period, and we will accept as many as we can support. Hackers pay no cost to participate (outside of personal transportation). 

We run three “main tracks”, which are overall themes (e.g. for this year these are student experience, interdisciplinary, and equitable technology). Hackers choose at most two main tracks to guide their development over the course of the hackathon. We do not impose any constraints on what students invent, aside from the implicit value of a project that aligns more closely with the chosen track’s theme. 

The event will run from Friday, November 7, beginning at 6:30pm with check in, until Sunday, November 9, ending at around 3pm (+/- 30min) The event will take place on Stony Brook University campus. 

There will be a main “hacking period” from 9pm on Friday until 7am on Sunday. During this period, students will be working on their projects, but other wellness, social, and technical workshops/events will be taking place concurrently. We currently have 6 workshop slots planned in which other student organizations may sign up to give workshops, however these are not exclusive to student organizations. We additionally have a designated Company/Sponsor Panel slot scheduled. These slots range from Friday night, through Saturday evening (barring overnight Friday-Saturday).

Judging will take place from 11am-1pm on Sunday, during which students will pitch their inventions, followed by an awards ceremony and closing.

value.description:
Shadow Puppet Show: Wrapped Presence
Sunday, November 9, Showings at 1 PM and 3 PM
Wang Center Theater


ADMISSION:

Free for children ages 5 and under.

Click HERE For Tickets

Caroline Borderies (puppeteer), Christian Barthod (puppeteer), Andre Bregegere (Music & Sounds), and Tessa Souter (narrator) present an original shadow puppet show with spare, intricate illustrations and lighting palettes that move from black and white to riotous color.


Inspired by Wonju Seo’s contemporary textile exhibition Through the Light: Contemporary Jogakbo at the Wang Center, this original shadow puppet performance follows four generations of Korean women. Through their stories, the cultural richness of jogakbo—from its intricate patchwork to its symbolic meanings of prosperity, happiness, and longevity—comes to life. With humor and heart, the show celebrates the artistry and eco-conscious elegance of this enduring tradition.

The 30-minute show will be followed by a behind-the-scenes tour with the artists.

Francisco Delgado will read from and discuss his novella, On Remembering My Friends, My First Job, and My Second-Favorite Weezer CD (Texas Review Press). Winner of the 2024 Clay Reynolds Novella Prize, the book tells the story of Cody Taitano, a CHamoru man who reflects on his teenage years in 1999 while navigating the complexities of parenthood during the COVID-19 pandemic.

Francisco Delgado is a CHamoru writer of poetry of prose, as well as of literary scholarship on contemporary Indigenous literatures. His novella, On Remembering My Friends, My First Job, and My Second-Favorite Weezer CD (Texas Review Press), won the 2024 Clay Reynolds Novella Prize. Other writing has recently been published in MANOA: A Pacific Journal of International Writing, Studies in the Novel, and Teaching English in the Two-Year College, and elsewhere. He teaches at Borough of Manhattan Community College/CUNY, where he created the first course devoted exclusively to the literatures of Native North America and the Indigenous Pacific.
